\v 6 Let \w your|strong="G1722"\w* \w word|strong="G3056"\w* \w always|strong="G3842"\w* \w be|strong="G1163"\w* \w with|strong="G1722"\w* \w grace|strong="G5485"\w*, seasoned \w with|strong="G1722"\w* salt,\f + \fr 4:6 \ft I wonder what “seasoned with salt” means. At least what we say should not be ‘insipid’, pointless.\f* \w to|strong="G1722"\w* \w know|strong="G1492"\w* \w how|strong="G4459"\w* \w you|strong="G5210"\w* \w ought|strong="G1163"\w* \w to|strong="G1722"\w* \w answer|strong="G3056"\w* \w each|strong="G1538"\w* \w one|strong="G1520"\w*.
\ms1 Concluding remarks
\p 
\v 7 \w Tychicus|strong="G5190"\w* \w will|strong="G2532"\w* \w tell|strong="G1107"\w* \w you|strong="G5210"\w* \w all|strong="G3956"\w* \w the|strong="G1722"\w* news \w about|strong="G2596"\w* \w me|strong="G1473"\w*; \w he|strong="G2532"\w* \w is|strong="G3588"\w* \w a|strong="G2532"\w* dear brother, \w a|strong="G2532"\w* \w faithful|strong="G4103"\w* \w minister|strong="G1249"\w* \w and|strong="G2532"\w* \w fellow|strong="G4889"\w* \w slave|strong="G4889"\w* \w in|strong="G1722"\w* \w the|strong="G1722"\w* \w Lord|strong="G2962"\w*.
\v 8 \w I|strong="G1473"\w* \w am|strong="G1473"\w* \w sending|strong="G3992"\w* \w him|strong="G3588"\w* \w to|strong="G1519"\w* \w you|strong="G5210"\w* \w for|strong="G1519"\w* \w this|strong="G3778"\w* \w very|strong="G2532"\w* \w purpose|strong="G3739"\w*, \w that|strong="G2443"\w* \w he|strong="G2532"\w* \w may|strong="G2532"\w* \w know|strong="G1097"\w* \w your|strong="G2532"\w* \w circumstances|strong="G3588"\w* \w and|strong="G2532"\w* \w encourage|strong="G3870"\w* \w your|strong="G2532"\w* \w hearts|strong="G2588"\w*,
\v 9 \w with|strong="G4862"\w* \w Onesimus|strong="G3682"\w*, \w a|strong="G2532"\w* \w faithful|strong="G4103"\w* \w and|strong="G2532"\w* beloved brother, \w who|strong="G3739"\w* \w is|strong="G1510"\w* \w one|strong="G3739"\w* \w of|strong="G1537"\w* \w you|strong="G5210"\w*; \w they|strong="G2532"\w* \w will|strong="G1510"\w* \w tell|strong="G1107"\w* \w you|strong="G5210"\w* \w everything|strong="G3956"\w* \w that|strong="G3739"\w* \w is|strong="G1510"\w* happening \w here|strong="G5602"\w*.
\p 
\v 10 Aristarchus \w my|strong="G1473"\w* \w fellow|strong="G4869"\w* \w prisoner|strong="G4869"\w* greets \w you|strong="G5210"\w*, \w as|strong="G2532"\w* \w does|strong="G1209"\w* \w Mark|strong="G3138"\w* \w the|strong="G2532"\w* cousin \w of|strong="G4012"\w* Barnabas (\w about|strong="G4012"\w* \w whom|strong="G3739"\w* \w you|strong="G5210"\w* \w received|strong="G2983"\w* \w instructions|strong="G1785"\w*; \w if|strong="G1437"\w* \w he|strong="G2532"\w* \w comes|strong="G2064"\w* \w to|strong="G4314"\w* \w you|strong="G5210"\w*, \w welcome|strong="G1209"\w* \w him|strong="G3588"\w*),\f + \fr 4:10 \ft Evidently Barnabas succeeded in ‘recovering’ Mark, which Paul here recognizes.\f*
\v 11 \w and|strong="G2532"\w* \w Jesus|strong="G2424"\w* \w who|strong="G3588"\w* \w is|strong="G1510"\w* \w called|strong="G3004"\w* \w Justus|strong="G2459"\w*. \w These|strong="G3778"\w* \w are|strong="G1510"\w* \w my|strong="G1473"\w* \w only|strong="G3441"\w* \w fellow|strong="G4904"\w* \w workers|strong="G4904"\w* \w for|strong="G1519"\w* \w the|strong="G2532"\w* Kingdom \w of|strong="G1537"\w* \w God|strong="G2316"\w* \w who|strong="G3588"\w* \w are|strong="G1510"\w* \w of|strong="G1537"\w* \w the|strong="G2532"\w* \w circumcision|strong="G4061"\w*; \w they|strong="G2532"\w* \w have|strong="G2532"\w* \w been|strong="G1510"\w* \w a|strong="G1096"\w* \w comfort|strong="G3931"\w* \w to|strong="G1519"\w* \w me|strong="G1473"\w*.
\p 
\v 12 \w Epaphras|strong="G1889"\w*, \w who|strong="G3588"\w* \w is|strong="G3588"\w* \w one|strong="G3956"\w* \w of|strong="G1537"\w* \w you|strong="G5210"\w*, \w a|strong="G2532"\w* \w slave|strong="G1401"\w* \w of|strong="G1537"\w* \w Christ|strong="G5547"\w*,\f + \fr 4:12 \ft Instead of “Christ”, perhaps 4% of the Greek manuscripts have ‘Christ Jesus’ (as in NIV, NASB, LB, TEV, etc.).\f* greets \w you|strong="G5210"\w*; \w he|strong="G2532"\w* \w is|strong="G3588"\w* \w always|strong="G3842"\w* wrestling \w in|strong="G1722"\w* \w prayer|strong="G4335"\w* \w for|strong="G5228"\w* \w you|strong="G5210"\w*, \w that|strong="G2443"\w* \w you|strong="G5210"\w* \w may|strong="G2532"\w* \w stand|strong="G2476"\w* \w perfect|strong="G5046"\w* \w and|strong="G2532"\w* \w complete|strong="G3956"\w* \w in|strong="G1722"\w* \w all|strong="G3956"\w* \w the|strong="G1722"\w* \w will|strong="G2307"\w* \w of|strong="G1537"\w* \w God|strong="G2316"\w*.\f + \fr 4:12 \ft We need more people like Epaphras, and that is a great way to pray.\f*
\v 13 \w I|strong="G2532"\w* \w bear|strong="G3140"\w* \w him|strong="G3588"\w* \w witness|strong="G3140"\w* \w that|strong="G3754"\w* \w he|strong="G2532"\w* \w has|strong="G2192"\w* \w a|strong="G2192"\w* \w great|strong="G4183"\w* zeal \w for|strong="G1063"\w* \w you|strong="G5210"\w*, \w and|strong="G2532"\w* \w for|strong="G1063"\w* \w those|strong="G3588"\w* \w in|strong="G1722"\w* \w Laodicea|strong="G2993"\w* \w and|strong="G2532"\w* \w those|strong="G3588"\w* \w in|strong="G1722"\w* \w Hierapolis|strong="G2404"\w*.
\p 
\v 14 \w Luke|strong="G3065"\w* \w the|strong="G2532"\w* beloved \w physician|strong="G2395"\w*\f + \fr 4:14 \ft Presumably this is where we get that title for Luke.\f* greets \w you|strong="G5210"\w*, \w also|strong="G2532"\w* \w Demas|strong="G1214"\w*.
\v 15 Greet \w the|strong="G1722"\w* brothers \w who|strong="G3588"\w* \w are|strong="G3588"\w* \w in|strong="G1722"\w* \w Laodicea|strong="G2993"\w*, \w and|strong="G2532"\w* \w Nymphas|strong="G3564"\w* \w and|strong="G2532"\w* \w the|strong="G1722"\w* \w congregation|strong="G1577"\w* \w at|strong="G1722"\w* \w his|strong="G1722"\w*\f + \fr 4:15 \ft Perhaps 1% of the Greek manuscripts, of objectively inferior quality, have ‘her’ (as in NIV, NASB, LB, TEV, etc.).\f* \w house|strong="G3624"\w*.
\p 
\v 16 \w Now|strong="G2532"\w* \w when|strong="G3752"\w* \w this|strong="G3588"\w* \w letter|strong="G1992"\w* \w has|strong="G2532"\w* \w been|strong="G2532"\w* read \w among|strong="G1722"\w* \w you|strong="G5210"\w*, see \w that|strong="G2443"\w* \w it|strong="G2532"\w* \w is|strong="G3588"\w* \w also|strong="G2532"\w* read \w in|strong="G1722"\w* \w the|strong="G1722"\w* Laodicean \w congregation|strong="G1577"\w*,\f + \fr 4:16 \ft Paul expected his letters to have a wide circulation.\f* \w and|strong="G2532"\w* \w that|strong="G2443"\w* \w you|strong="G5210"\w* \w in|strong="G1722"\w* turn read \w the|strong="G1722"\w* \w letter|strong="G1992"\w* \w from|strong="G1537"\w* \w Laodicea|strong="G2993"\w*.\f + \fr 4:16 \ft We have no copy of this letter, so presumably it was not inspired, and therefore not preserved. It is possible, even probable, that Paul wrote other letters that were not preserved.\f*
\p 
\v 17 \w And|strong="G2532"\w* \w say|strong="G3004"\w* \w to|strong="G2443"\w* Archippus, “See \w to|strong="G2443"\w* \w it|strong="G2532"\w* \w that|strong="G2443"\w* \w you|strong="G3739"\w* \w complete|strong="G4137"\w* \w the|strong="G1722"\w* work \w that|strong="G2443"\w* \w you|strong="G3739"\w* \w received|strong="G3880"\w* \w in|strong="G1722"\w* \w the|strong="G1722"\w* \w Lord|strong="G2962"\w*.”\f + \fr 4:17 \ft This personal word is unusual in a letter to the church. Since Paul had never been to Colosse, he must have known Archippus from somewhere else, but happened to know that he was in Colosse at that time. However, that exhortation is good for all of us. The older I get, the larger that exhortation looms in my mind.\f*
\ms1 Sign-off
\p 
\v 18 \w This|strong="G3588"\w* greeting \w is|strong="G3588"\w* \w in|strong="G3326"\w* \w my|strong="G1699"\w* \w own|strong="G1699"\w* \w hand|strong="G5495"\w*: \w Paul|strong="G3972"\w*.\f + \fr 4:18 \ft The letter was dictated to a scribe or secretary, but Paul wrote the last line himself; this was his signature, authenticating the letter.\f* \w Remember|strong="G3421"\w* \w my|strong="G1699"\w* \w chains|strong="G1199"\w*. \w The|strong="G3588"\w* \w Grace|strong="G5485"\w* \w be|strong="G3588"\w* \w with|strong="G3326"\w* \w you|strong="G5210"\w*. Amen. 
